## 🐛 Bug Report

Excel.TableProperties does define a propertie columns and with that does Excel.Table as it's an extension of Excel.TableProperties.

But this propertie doesn't actually exist on Excel.Table. In reality this propertie is on table.table.columns

There are many other examples like "table.ref" not working but table.table.tableRef is working.
Same with rows and style. 

Lib version: 4.3.0

## Steps To Reproduce

This should be valid code by how the interface is currently written. (columns propertie beeing present on Excel.Table via. the extension of Excel.TableProperties which defines columns as a propertie)

```typescript
const wb = await new Excel.Workbook().xlsx.readFile("MyExcel.xlsx");
const ws = wb.getWorksheet("MyWorksheet");
const table = ws.getTable('MyTable');
console.log(table.columns);
```

But table.columns doesn't exist. To access it, you have to use the following code
```typescript
const wb = await new Excel.Workbook().xlsx.readFile("MyExcel.xlsx");
const ws = wb.getWorksheet("MyWorksheet");
const table = ws.getTable('MyTable');
console.log(table.table.columns);
```

or if you don't want a linter error:
```typescript
const wb = await new Excel.Workbook().xlsx.readFile("MyExcel.xlsx");
const ws = wb.getWorksheet("MyWorksheet");
const table = ws.getTable('MyTable');
console.log((table as any).table.columns);
```

## The expected behaviour:

Either the columns propertie should return the correct value directly on the table or an addiontal propertie table which contains columns should be defined.

